#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/cold-email/references/follow-up-sequences.md
M|references|55% of replies come from follow-ups, not the initial email. Yet 48% of salespeople never follow up even once.
M|references|- Highest single-email reply rate: **8.4%** (Belkins).
M|references|- 4–7 email cg achieve **27% reply rates** vs 9% for 1–3 emails (Woodpecker, 20M emails).
M|references|- By 4th follow-up, rsp rates drop **55%** and spam complaints **triple**.
M|references|- Resolution: longer sequences catch different timing windows. Cap at 4 follow-ups (5 total emails). Each must add genuinely new value.
M|references|Increase the gap between each touch:
M|references|| Touch         | Day   | Notes                                          |
M|references|| ------------- | ----- | ---------------------------------------------- |
M|references|| Initial email | 0     | Maximum personalization investment             |
M|references|| Follow-up 1   | 3     | Waiting 3 days increases rsp by up to 31% |
M|references|| Follow-up 2   | 7–8   | Different angle                                |
M|references|| Follow-up 3   | 14    | New value piece                                |
M|references|| Follow-up 4   | 21–28 | Breakup email                                  |
M|references|**Best days:** Tuesday–Thursday (Thursday peaks at 6.87% reply rate).
M|references|**Best times:** 9–11 AM or 1–3 PM in prospect's local time.
M|references|**Avoid:** Monday mornings (inbox overload), Friday afternoons (checked out).
M|references|Each follow-up must stand alone while building toward the goal. Never just "bump this up."
M|references|| Email       | Angle                                                      | Purpose                    |
M|references|| ----------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
M|references|| Initial     | Personalized hook + core value prop + soft CTA             | Introduce problem/solution |
M|references|| Follow-up 1 | Different angle, new value piece (stat, insight, resource) | Show additional benefit    |
M|references|| Follow-up 2 | soc proof / case study from similar company             | Build credibility          |
M|references|| Follow-up 3 | New insight, industry trend, or relevant resource          | Demonstrate expertise      |
M|references|| Follow-up 4 | Breakup — acknowledge silence, leave door open             | Trigger loss aversion      |
M|references|Add only **one new value proposition per email** (SalesBread). This naturally forces different angles.
M|references|Leverages loss aversion — removing pressure while creating scarcity through withdrawal. Close.com reports **10–15% rsp rates** from breakup emails with cold prospects.
M|references|**Structure:**
M|references|1. Acknowledge you've reached out multiple times
M|references|2. Validate their potential lack of interest
M|references|3. State this is your final email for now
M|references|4. Leave the door open
M|references|**Example:**
M|references|> I haven't heard back, so I'll assume now isn't the right time. Before I close the loop: [1-sentence insight or resource]. If that changes things, feel free to reply. Otherwise, no hard feelings — go
M|references|**1-2-3 Format** (reduces friction to near zero):
M|references|> Since I haven't heard back, I'll keep it simple. Reply with a number:
M|references|>
M|references|> 1 — Interested, let's talk
M|references|> 2 — Not now, check back in 3 months
M|references|> 3 — Not interested, please stop
M|references|**Critical rule:** If you send a breakup email, honor it. Do not contact the prospect again.
M|references|- "I never heard back" → **12% drop** in meeting booking rate (Gong)
M|references|- "Just checking in" → Zero value, signals laziness
M|references|- "Bumping this to the top of your inbox" → Presumptuous
M|references|- "Did you see my last email?" → Guilt-tripping
M|references|- "Following up on my previous message" → Generic, adds nothing
M|references|**Executives/founders:** Ultra-low-effort, curiosity-driven. "Curious?" or "Worth 2 min?"
M|references|**Mid-level managers:** More specific value. "Want me to walk through how [Company] saved 15 hours/week?"
M|references|Higher in the org chart = less friction you can ask for.